TUCSON The City Council
ordered preparation of public
accommodations ordinance by a
special committee within two
weeks.


Action came at a hearing at
which representatives of 20 or
CARNATIONS, plus three individ-
uals, spoke favoring the proposed
ordinance to prohibit discrimina-
ton because of race, creed or
national origin in such places as
restaurants, taverns and hotels.


Councilmen James Corbett and
M. J. Southland, City Manager
Mark Keane and City Attorney
Calvin Webster we're appointed
as the committee to draft the
ordinance.

For Accommodu fion
Bill Passage

The Presbytery Of Phoenix, of
the United Presbyterian Church
passed unanimously decision to
oppose the initiative petition be-
ing circulated which would for
bid the public school instruction
of "such specified theories as
are designated "arheism defined
as sectarian doctrine.''


The statement continued, 1--WE
commend to our congregations
the responsible nurture of our
people in the Christian faith. We
would maintain for our public
schools a climate where our
children and teachers can pursue
freely search for truth without
rigid legal restrictions or ar
bitrary theological perspectives.
To this end, we urge the members
of our local congregations not to
sign this petition

City Countil has endorsed
program designed to help the
most "disadvantaged area" of the
city. Formerly known as elmer
City, the program was renamed
Operation LEAP" designating
Leadership and Education for
the Advancement of Phoenix"
Mayor Graham reported the fol-
lowing figures:


/. One out of 4 residents lives
in the "project area"


2. More than l out of every
3 houses in the area is dete-
riorated or diplapidated.


8. The residents of this area
earn an average of $500 less
per family per year than those
in the rest of the community.


4. There is 2 W times more
unemployment in this area than
in the rest of the community.


S. Nearly "a of every 100
youngsters in this area live in
one-parent families.


Graham noted additional sta
tistics. but pointed out the phil
osophy of Operation LEAP is
such that all activities and pro-
grams are to be "planned and
acted upon with, not for. the af-
fected persons in the area"


The majority membership OF
all committees, 1t was noted,
will be residents of the area.
Operation LEAP will have the
following task forces or working
committees: Education: Business
and Industrial Development;
Youth Council: Housing: Health,
Welfare and Recreation; and
Neighborhood Councils.


Mayor Graham indicated that
technical assistance to the COM
mittees will be provided by such
groups as Community Council,
Phoenix Union High School Sys-
tenn, State Employment Service,
Chamber of Commerce. Urban
League, Phoenix Project for Pu-
pil Motivation, and Arizona State
University.

Mrs. Leona Huntley. l443 E.
Washington. was driving her auto
across the railroad crossing at
10th Street near Jackson on June
s when the train hit her car.


She had started to cross after
watching a train and engine pass.
Before she could cross another

train approached.


The impact threw Mrs. Hunt
ley into her windshield. she was
taken to Good Samaritan Hospital
for observation.


Mrs. Huntley received minor
bruises. but her car was total
loss.
